06952nam a22009135i 9780812209457DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024024067  a(OCoLC)979724638  a97808122094577 a10.9783/97808122094572doi  a(DE-B1597)449790  a(OCoLC)859162220  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0060902bisacsh04a220.600aJewish Biblical Interpretation and Cultural Exchange :bComparative Exegesis in Context /ced. by David Stern, Natalie B. Dohrmann. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b7 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: On Comparative Biblical Exegesis–Interpretation, Influence, Appropriation -- t1. Interpreting Torah Traditions in Psalm 105 -- t2. Cain: Son of God or Son of Satan? -- t3. Manumission and Transformation in Jewish and Roman Law -- t4. Lessons from Jerome’s Jewish Teachers: Exegesis and Cultural Interaction in Late Antique Palestine -- t5. Ancient Jewish Interpretation of the Song of Songs in a Comparative Context -- t6. Patriarchy, Primogeniture, and Polemic in the Exegetical Traditions of Judaism and Islam -- t7. May Karaites Eat Chicken? Indeterminacy in Sectarian Halakhic Exegesis -- t8. Early Islamic Exegesis as Legal Theory: How Qur’anic Wisdom (Hikma) Became the Sunna of the Prophet -- t9. Interpreting Scripture in and through Liturgy: Exegesis of Mass Propers in the Middle Ages -- t10. Exegesis and Polemic in Rashbam’s Commentary on the Song of Songs -- t11. Literal versus Carnal: George of Siena’s Christian Reading of Jewish Exegesis -- t12. Christian and Jewish Iconographies of Job in Fifteenth-Century Italy -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Persons -- tIndex of Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiblical interpretation is not simply study of the Bible's meaning. Historically, it has also served as a primary medium for cultural and religious exchange between the great religious traditions of the West. Focusing on moments of signal interest in the history of Jewish, Christian, and Islamic scriptural interpretation from the ancient, medieval, and early modern periods, Jewish Biblical Interpretation and Cultural Exchange offers a unique comparative perspective. Each of the essays treats its subject in relation to the larger cultural context and to other contemporary interpretative traditions. Sources and authors examined in the book include late biblical and early postbiblical compositions, rabbinic legal and homiletical interpretation, Jerome and other early Christian exegetes, Islamic exegesis in both the Qur'an and early Muslim tradition, medieval Jewish and Christian exegetes, and biblical interpretation as evidenced in early modern illustrations of biblical scenes.The histories of Jewish, Christian, and Islamic interpretation are presented not merely as parallel but as deeply interrelated, not only as reacting and polemicizing against each other but often as appropriating the tools and methods of their rival traditions. Biblical exegesis thus emerges as a forum of active and intense cultural exchange. The volume comes at a crucial time in the study of Jewish relations with Christianity and Islam, and shows how deeply connected and intertwined these three religious traditions truly are.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDohrman